President Trump and Prime Minister Abe of Japan have announced the first stage of a new trade agreement between the two countries. The agreement includes the opening of new markets in Japan for approximately $7 billion worth of American agricultural products, as well as commitments on $40 billion of digital trade. The deal aims to reduce the chronic trade deficit between the two countries and deepen their economic ties. Negotiations will continue on remaining areas of interest to achieve a final comprehensive agreement. The leaders expressed their gratitude for the successful negotiations and highlighted the benefits of the agreement for consumers, producers, and workers in both countries.